<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">41702025</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>12</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>12</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1873-3778</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>1773</Volume><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Apr</Month><Day>26</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Journal of chromatography. A</Title><ISOAbbreviation>J Chromatogr A</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Halloysite nanotubes-incorporated ionic liquid-modified organic polymer monolith for the spin-tip solid-phase extraction of dexmedetomidine from whole blood.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>466802</StartPage><MedlinePgn>466802</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.chroma.2026.466802</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S0021-9673(26)00132-9</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>Herein, a novel halloysite nanotubes-incorporated ionic liquid-modified organic polymer monolith (HNTs-IL monolith) was synthesized and used for the first time for the highly efficient and selective spin-tip solid phase extraction of dexmedetomidine from complex whole blood samples. The adsorption capacity of HNTs-IL monolith for dexmedetomidine was remarkably improved by introducing HNTs, which was up to 33.8 mg/g. Furthermore, the HNTs-IL monolith demonstrated excellent reusability, enduring up to 100 extraction cycles. The established method exhibits a wide linear range (0.10-10.00 ng/mL), a low limit of detection (0.01 ng/mL), less sample and sorbent consumption (50 &#x3bc;L of whole blood, 15 mg of sorbent), negligible matrix effect (103%), excellent reproducibility (intra-day RSDs: 2.7-7.3%; inter-day RSDs: 5.6-9.8%), and achieved high recoveries in whole blood samples (89.7-98.3%). This work offers a robust and practical tool for the sensitive monitoring of dexmedetomidine in clinical applications.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2026 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Ouyang</LastName><ForeName>Menglin</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>The First Affiliated Hospital of Ningbo University, Ningbo 315020, China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Zhang</LastName><ForeName>Biao</ForeName><Initials>B</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Affiliated Hospital of Hebei University, Baoding 071002, China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Chen</LastName><ForeName>Yihui</ForeName><Initials>Y</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Ningbo Customs Technology Center, Ningbo 315040, China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Qiao</LastName><ForeName>Xiaoqiang</ForeName><Initials>X</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>College of Pharmaceutical Sciences, Key Laboratory of Medicinal Chemistry and Molecular Diagnosis, Ministry of Education, Hebei University, Baoding 071002, China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Zhang</LastName><ForeName>Yiwei</ForeName><Initials>Y</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>The First Affiliated Hospital of Ningbo University, Ningbo 315020, China. Electronic address: fyyzhangyiwei@nbu.edu.cn.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Wang</LastName><ForeName>Tingting</ForeName><Initials>T</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>School of Materials and Chemical Engineering, Ningbo University of Technology, Ningbo 315211, China. Electronic address: wangtingting@nbut.edu.cn.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><ArticleDate D